rg/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor women at the early modern courts, clothing and jewellery were essential elements in their political arsenal, enabling them to signal their dynastic value, to promote loyalty to their marital court and to advance political agendas. This is the first collection of essays to examine how elite women in early modern Europe marshalled clothing and jewellery for political ends. With essays encompassing women who traversed courts in Denmark, England, France, Germany, Habsburg Austria, Italy, Portugal, Spain and Sweden, the contributions cover a broad range of elite women from different courts and religious backgrounds as well as varying noble ranks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  adress.  ajewelry.  apolitics.  aqueens.  aweddings.1 aClaxton, Juliet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCockram, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aField, Jemma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrieling, Kirsten O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffey, Erin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriffey, Erin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHayward, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolm, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLublin, Robert I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMansfield, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOliván-Santalies